latestPosts.caption:
I have been told all my life that never show people if something is going wrong in your life. instead, pretend everything is okay. never show them your bad side. but how easy it is for people to judge that you're actually happy when you're not. easy for them to say "arey ise kya hi ho sakta hai?" "look at her stories she's so happy" "she probably doesn't care about other people" "look at her living her life to the fullest". all these judgements are made after they see your social media. being too active on social, sharing some happy bits and pieces of your life, doesn't make you weak or bad. if someone is starting something good with you, please do give it a thought that they are sharing because they feel safe here. they are sharing without the fear of judgement. 

i used to be way too active on social media. i was at a point where i used to share everything because it made me happy! it makes me feel good. i treat my account as my digital diary.
It's true, isn't it? A few happy posts don't erase the struggles someone might be facing privately. And as i said, sharing those positive moments can sometimes be a way of finding joy and connection, a digital diary of sorts. It takes courage to be vulnerable and share, and it's disheartening when those glimpses are met with assumptions rather than understanding.

The pressure to always appear "okay" can be incredibly taxing. It's like carrying a hidden weight, and it can feel isolating when people assume everything is easy for you based on what they see on a screen. Your perspective about creating a safe space for sharing without fear of judgment is a valuable one. It highlights the potential for social media to be a positive tool for connection when approached with empathy and understanding.

It's a delicate balance, isn't it? Navigating how much to share and how to protect ourselves from misinterpretations. Your reflections on your own social media use and the reasons behind it are insightful. It's a reminder that there's often a story behind the story, and that kindness and open-mindedness go a long way in our interactions, both online and offline.
you're not alone!✨ share your stories in the comments.

two years ago, on 14th October when i got the chance to meet him for the first time, i wasn't able to make it. 
two years later, on 14th October i got to know that he is coming to bbsr for an event! obviously i had to register the minute i heard the news!🥹 
and yesterday when i saw him for the first time, the moment i saw him coming in, tears rolled down my eyes. ( i started ugly crying that even the cameraman took my pictures!😭)
i have been manifesting this moment everyday!! i can proudly say my 11:11 came true!!🧿🥹. the goosebumps i got when we shook hands!😭🩷 
i still remember the first time he commented on my reel and he reshared it on his story too!! at that moment i never knew that I'd get this lucky to see him from this close!!
but i guess this is not the end. is it? nooo!!
Rohit, thank you soo much for the best day yesterday!🥹🩷 you're truly the most humble person!🩷 manifesting again to see you soon!!🧿
couldn't take a picture with you this time but next time for sure 🥹
xoxo,
Kanisha 🎀

latestPosts.caption:
After eight long years away from the stage, I finally stepped back into the spotlight—this time as the anchor of a storytelling festival at the beautiful Bakul Foundation. The moment I held the mic, a quiet storm of nerves and nostalgia swirled inside me. But as the lights hit, and the stories began to unfold, something within me stirred—like an old flame I thought had burned out. I was overwhelmed, yes, but in the best way possible. It felt like coming home to a version of myself I’d almost forgotten. The joy, the adrenaline, the energy of the audience—all of it reminded me why I ever fell in love with the stage in the first place. Here's to finding pieces of ourselves we didn’t know we’d lost, and to the courage it takes to reclaim them. 🌟

#OnStageAgain #StorytellingMagic #BakulFoundation #FullCircleMoments
